The Chronicle Nqobile Tshili, Chronicle Reporter BULAWAYO on Monday morning started Covid-19 vaccination programme for frontline workers with Health Service Board chairman Dr Paulinus Sikosana being the first to be inoculated. <img class="alignnone wp-image-533073 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/02/Byo-Vaccination-2.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/02/Byo-Vaccination-2.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/02/Byo-Vaccination-2-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" />  Dr Sikosana took the jab exactly at 11:15AM at the United Bulawayo Hospitals (UBH) outpatient department. He encouraged other frontline workers to do the same.   Government last week launched the Covid-19 vaccination programme after receiving a 200 000 sinopharm vaccine donation from China. Under phase one of the Covid-19 vaccination programme, health workers, Zimbabwe Revenue Authority (Zimra), ports of entry personnel and village health workers.  About 6 600 people are expected to be vaccinated in Bulawayo.  More to followâ€¦